he Sanctuary hosted one of the preeminent athletic festivals of ancient Greece, the Nemean Games. Just as the Olympics were celebrated in connection with the cult of Pelops at Olympia, the games at Nemea were founded on the worship of the hero Opheltes. The Shrine of Opheltes in the Sanctuary of Zeus at Nemea offers one of the best examples of an ancient Greek hero cult documented in the archaeological record. This final and most significant volume in the Excavations at Nemea series presents the results of the excavation of the Shrine from 1979 through 2001 and analyzes the Shrine's features and contents in order to understand its history and use. A study of the literary and artistic evidence about the myth and cult of Opheltes contextualizes the archaeological findings and illuminates the hero's significance to the Sanctuary and its renowned festival, the Nemean Games.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCultszGreece. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zGreece. 0aHero worshipzGreece. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  a1979.  a1980s.  a1990s.  a2001.  aacademic.  aancient greece.  aancient greek history.  aancient nemea.  aancient world.  aanthropology.  aantiquity.  aarchaeological record.  aarchaeological.  aarchaeology.  aathletic festival.  acult of pelops.  aevidence.  aexcavation.  agreek hero.  aheroes.  amythology.  anemean games.  aolympia.  aolympics.  aopheltes.  asanctuary of zeus.  asanctuary.  ascholarly.  ashrine of opheltes.  auniversity of california.  aworld history.1 aMackinnon, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029492940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096787